   1 """scandir, a better directory iterator and faster os.walk(), now in the Python 3.5 stdlib
   2 
   3 scandir() is a generator version of os.listdir() that returns an
   4 iterator over files in a directory, and also exposes the extra
   5 information most OSes provide while iterating files in a directory
   6 (such as type and stat information).
   7 
   8 This module also includes a version of os.walk() that uses scandir()
   9 to speed it up significantly.
  10 
  11 See README.md or https://github.com/benhoyt/scandir for rationale and
  12 docs, or read PEP 471 (https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0471/) for
  13 more details on its inclusion into Python 3.5
  14 
  15 scandir is released under the new BSD 3-clause license. See
  16 LICENSE.txt for the full license text.
  17 """
  18

  69 class GenericDirEntry(object):
  70     __slots__ = ('name', '_stat', '_lstat', '_scandir_path', '_path')
  71 
  72     def __init__(self, scandir_path, name):
  73         self._scandir_path = scandir_path
  74         self.name = name
  75         self._stat = None
  76         self._lstat = None
  77         self._path = None
  78 
  79     @property
  80     def path(self):
  81         if self._path is None:
  82             self._path = join(self._scandir_path, self.name)
  83         return self._path
  84 
  85     def stat(self, follow_symlinks=True):
  86         if follow_symlinks:
  87             if self._stat is None:
  88                 self._stat = stat(self.path)
  89             return self._stat
  90         else:
  91             if self._lstat is None:
  92                 self._lstat = lstat(self.path)
  93             return self._lstat
  94 
  95     # The code duplication below is intentional: this is for slightly
  96     # better performance on systems that fall back to GenericDirEntry.
  97     # It avoids an additional attribute lookup and method call, which
  98     # are relatively slow on CPython.
  99     def is_dir(self, follow_symlinks=True):
 100         try:
 101             st = self.stat(follow_symlinks=follow_symlinks)
 102         except OSError as e:
 103             if e.errno != ENOENT:
 104                 raise
 105             return False  # Path doesn't exist or is a broken symlink
 106         return st.st_mode & 0o170000 == S_IFDIR
 107 
 108     def is_file(self, follow_symlinks=True):
 109         try:
 110             st = self.stat(follow_symlinks=follow_symlinks)
 111         except OSError as e:
 112             if e.errno != ENOENT:
 113                 raise
 114             return False  # Path doesn't exist or is a broken symlink
 115         return st.st_mode & 0o170000 == S_IFREG
 116 
 117     def is_symlink(self):
 118         try:
 119             st = self.stat(follow_symlinks=False)
 120         except OSError as e:
 121             if e.errno != ENOENT:
 122                 raise
 123             return False  # Path doesn't exist or is a broken symlink
 124         return st.st_mode & 0o170000 == S_IFLNK
 125 
 126     def inode(self):
 127         st = self.stat(follow_symlinks=False)
 128         return st.st_ino
 129 
 130     def __str__(self):
 131         return '<{0}: {1!r}>'.format(self.__class__.__name__, self.name)
 132 
 133     __repr__ = __str__

 136 def _scandir_generic(path=unicode('.')):
 137     """Like os.listdir(), but yield DirEntry objects instead of returning
 138     a list of names.
 139     """
 140     for name in listdir(path):
 141         yield GenericDirEntry(path, name)

 145     def scandir_generic(path=unicode('.')):
 146         if isinstance(path, bytes):
 147             raise TypeError("os.scandir() doesn't support bytes path on Windows, use Unicode instead")
 148         return _scandir_generic(path)
 149     scandir_generic.__doc__ = _scandir_generic.__doc__
 150 else:
 151     scandir_generic = _scandir_generic

 162         # Various constants from windows.h

 168         # Numer of seconds between 1601-01-01 and 1970-01-01
 169         SECONDS_BETWEEN_EPOCHS = 11644473600

 193         Win32StatResult = collections.namedtuple('Win32StatResult', [
 194             'st_mode',
 195             'st_ino',
 196             'st_dev',
 197             'st_nlink',
 198             'st_uid',
 199             'st_gid',
 200             'st_size',
 201             'st_atime',
 202             'st_mtime',
 203             'st_ctime',
 204             'st_atime_ns',
 205             'st_mtime_ns',
 206             'st_ctime_ns',
 207             'st_file_attributes',

 210         def filetime_to_time(filetime):
 211             """Convert Win32 FILETIME to time since Unix epoch in seconds."""
 212             total = filetime.dwHighDateTime << 32 | filetime.dwLowDateTime
 213             return total / 10000000 - SECONDS_BETWEEN_EPOCHS
 214 
 215         def find_data_to_stat(data):
 216             """Convert Win32 FIND_DATA struct to stat_result."""
 217             # First convert Win32 dwFileAttributes to st_mode
 218             attributes = data.dwFileAttributes
 219             st_mode = 0
 220             if attributes & FILE_ATTRIBUTE_DIRECTORY:
 221                 st_mode |= S_IFDIR | 0o111
 222             else:
 223                 st_mode |= S_IFREG
 224             if attributes & FILE_ATTRIBUTE_READONLY:
 225                 st_mode |= 0o444
 226             else:
 227                 st_mode |= 0o666
 228             if (attributes & FILE_ATTRIBUTE_REPARSE_POINT and
 229                     data.dwReserved0 == IO_REPARSE_TAG_SYMLINK):
 230                 st_mode ^= st_mode & 0o170000
 231                 st_mode |= S_IFLNK
 232 
 233             st_size = data.nFileSizeHigh << 32 | data.nFileSizeLow
 234             st_atime = filetime_to_time(data.ftLastAccessTime)
 235             st_mtime = filetime_to_time(data.ftLastWriteTime)
 236             st_ctime = filetime_to_time(data.ftCreationTime)
 237 
 238             # Some fields set to zero per CPython's posixmodule.c: st_ino, st_dev,
 239             # st_nlink, st_uid, st_gid
 240             return Win32StatResult(st_mode, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, st_size,
 241                                    st_atime, st_mtime, st_ctime,
 242                                    int(st_atime * 1000000000),
 243                                    int(st_mtime * 1000000000),
 244                                    int(st_ctime * 1000000000),
 245                                    attributes)
 246 
 247         class Win32DirEntryPython(object):
 248             __slots__ = ('name', '_stat', '_lstat', '_find_data', '_scandir_path', '_path', '_inode')
 249 
 250             def __init__(self, scandir_path, name, find_data):
 251                 self._scandir_path = scandir_path
 252                 self.name = name
 253                 self._stat = None
 254                 self._lstat = None
 255                 self._find_data = find_data
 256                 self._path = None
 257                 self._inode = None
 258 
 259             @property
 260             def path(self):
 261                 if self._path is None:
 262                     self._path = join(self._scandir_path, self.name)
 263                 return self._path
 264 
 265             def stat(self, follow_symlinks=True):
 266                 if follow_symlinks:
 267                     if self._stat is None:
 268                         if self.is_symlink():
 269                             # It's a symlink, call link-following stat()
 270                             self._stat = stat(self.path)
 271                         else:
 272                             # Not a symlink, stat is same as lstat value
 273                             if self._lstat is None:
 274                                 self._lstat = find_data_to_stat(self._find_data)
 275                             self._stat = self._lstat
 276                     return self._stat
 277                 else:
 278                     if self._lstat is None:
 279                         # Lazily convert to stat object, because it's slow
 280                         # in Python, and often we only need is_dir() etc
 281                         self._lstat = find_data_to_stat(self._find_data)
 282                     return self._lstat
 283 
 284             def is_dir(self, follow_symlinks=True):
 285                 is_symlink = self.is_symlink()
 286                 if follow_symlinks and is_symlink:
 287                     try:
 288                         return self.stat().st_mode & 0o170000 == S_IFDIR
 289                     except OSError as e:
 290                         if e.errno != ENOENT:
 291                             raise
 292                         return False
 293                 elif is_symlink:
 294                     return False
 295                 else:
 296                     return (self._find_data.dwFileAttributes &
 297                             FILE_ATTRIBUTE_DIRECTORY != 0)
 298 
 299             def is_file(self, follow_symlinks=True):
 300                 is_symlink = self.is_symlink()
 301                 if follow_symlinks and is_symlink:
 302                     try:
 303                         return self.stat().st_mode & 0o170000 == S_IFREG
 304                     except OSError as e:
 305                         if e.errno != ENOENT:
 306                             raise
 307                         return False
 308                 elif is_symlink:
 309                     return False
 310                 else:
 311                     return (self._find_data.dwFileAttributes &
 312                             FILE_ATTRIBUTE_DIRECTORY == 0)
 313 
 314             def is_symlink(self):
 315                 return (self._find_data.dwFileAttributes &
 316                             FILE_ATTRIBUTE_REPARSE_POINT != 0 and
 317                         self._find_data.dwReserved0 == IO_REPARSE_TAG_SYMLINK)
 318 
 319             def inode(self):
 320                 if self._inode is None:
 321                     self._inode = lstat(self.path).st_ino
 322                 return self._inode
 323 
 324             def __str__(self):
 325                 return '<{0}: {1!r}>'.format(self.__class__.__name__, self.name)
 326 
 327             __repr__ = __str__

 329         def win_error(error, filename):
 330             exc = WindowsError(error, ctypes.FormatError(error))
 331             exc.filename = filename
 332             return exc
 333 
 334         def _scandir_python(path=unicode('.')):
 335             """Like os.listdir(), but yield DirEntry objects instead of returning
 336             a list of names.
 337             """
 338             # Call FindFirstFile and handle errors
 339             if isinstance(path, bytes):
 340                 is_bytes = True
 341                 filename = join(path.decode('mbcs', 'strict'), '*.*')
 342             else:
 343                 is_bytes = False
 344                 filename = join(path, '*.*')
 345             data = wintypes.WIN32_FIND_DATAW()
 346             data_p = ctypes.byref(data)
 347             handle = FindFirstFile(filename, data_p)
 348             if handle == INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE:
 349                 error = ctypes.GetLastError()
 350                 if error == ERROR_FILE_NOT_FOUND:
 351                     # No files, don't yield anything
 352                     return
 353                 raise win_error(error, path)
 354 
 355             # Call FindNextFile in a loop, stopping when no more files
 356             try:
 357                 while True:
 358                     # Skip '.' and '..' (current and parent directory), but
 359                     # otherwise yield (filename, stat_result) tuple
 360                     name = data.cFileName
 361                     if name not in ('.', '..'):
 362                         if is_bytes:
 363                             name = name.encode('mbcs', 'replace')
 364                         yield Win32DirEntryPython(path, name, data)
 365 
 366                     data = wintypes.WIN32_FIND_DATAW()
 367                     data_p = ctypes.byref(data)
 368                     success = FindNextFile(handle, data_p)
 369                     if not success:
 370                         error = ctypes.GetLastError()
 371                         if error == ERROR_NO_MORE_FILES:
 372                             break
 373                         raise win_error(error, path)
 374             finally:
 375                 if not FindClose(handle):
 376                     raise win_error(ctypes.GetLastError(), path)
 377

 402 # Linux, OS X, and BSD implementation
 403 elif sys.platform.startswith(('linux', 'darwin', 'sunos5')) or 'bsd' in sys.platform:

 409         DIR_p = ctypes.c_void_p
 410 
 411         # Rather annoying how the dirent struct is slightly different on each
 412         # platform. The only fields we care about are d_name and d_type.
 413         class Dirent(ctypes.Structure):
 414             if sys.platform.startswith('linux'):
 415                 _fields_ = (
 416                     ('d_ino', ctypes.c_ulong),
 417                     ('d_off', ctypes.c_long),
 418                     ('d_reclen', ctypes.c_ushort),
 419                     ('d_type', ctypes.c_byte),
 420                     ('d_name', ctypes.c_char * 256),
 421                 )
 422             elif 'openbsd' in sys.platform:
 423                 _fields_ = (
 424                     ('d_ino', ctypes.c_uint64),
 425                     ('d_off', ctypes.c_uint64),
 426                     ('d_reclen', ctypes.c_uint16),
 427                     ('d_type', ctypes.c_uint8),
 428                     ('d_namlen', ctypes.c_uint8),
 429                     ('__d_padding', ctypes.c_uint8 * 4),
 430                     ('d_name', ctypes.c_char * 256),
 431                 )
 432             else:
 433                 _fields_ = (
 434                     ('d_ino', ctypes.c_uint32),  # must be uint32, not ulong
 435                     ('d_reclen', ctypes.c_ushort),
 436                     ('d_type', ctypes.c_byte),
 437                     ('d_namlen', ctypes.c_byte),
 438                     ('d_name', ctypes.c_char * 256),
 439                 )

 441         DT_UNKNOWN = 0
 442         DT_DIR = 4
 443         DT_REG = 8
 444         DT_LNK = 10
 445 
 446         Dirent_p = ctypes.POINTER(Dirent)
 447         Dirent_pp = ctypes.POINTER(Dirent_p)

 449         libc = ctypes.CDLL(ctypes.util.find_library('c'), use_errno=True)
 450         opendir = libc.opendir
 451         opendir.argtypes = [ctypes.c_char_p]
 452         opendir.restype = DIR_p
 453 
 454         readdir_r = libc.readdir_r
 455         readdir_r.argtypes = [DIR_p, Dirent_p, Dirent_pp]
 456         readdir_r.restype = ctypes.c_int
 457 
 458         closedir = libc.closedir
 459         closedir.argtypes = [DIR_p]
 460         closedir.restype = ctypes.c_int

 464         class PosixDirEntry(object):
 465             __slots__ = ('name', '_d_type', '_stat', '_lstat', '_scandir_path', '_path', '_inode')
 466 
 467             def __init__(self, scandir_path, name, d_type, inode):
 468                 self._scandir_path = scandir_path
 469                 self.name = name
 470                 self._d_type = d_type
 471                 self._inode = inode
 472                 self._stat = None
 473                 self._lstat = None
 474                 self._path = None
 475 
 476             @property
 477             def path(self):
 478                 if self._path is None:
 479                     self._path = join(self._scandir_path, self.name)
 480                 return self._path
 481 
 482             def stat(self, follow_symlinks=True):
 483                 if follow_symlinks:
 484                     if self._stat is None:
 485                         if self.is_symlink():
 486                             self._stat = stat(self.path)
 487                         else:
 488                             if self._lstat is None:
 489                                 self._lstat = lstat(self.path)
 490                             self._stat = self._lstat
 491                     return self._stat
 492                 else:
 493                     if self._lstat is None:
 494                         self._lstat = lstat(self.path)
 495                     return self._lstat
 496 
 497             def is_dir(self, follow_symlinks=True):
 498                 if (self._d_type == DT_UNKNOWN or
 499                         (follow_symlinks and self.is_symlink())):
 500                     try:
 501                         st = self.stat(follow_symlinks=follow_symlinks)
 502                     except OSError as e:
 503                         if e.errno != ENOENT:
 504                             raise
 505                         return False
 506                     return st.st_mode & 0o170000 == S_IFDIR
 507                 else:
 508                     return self._d_type == DT_DIR
 509 
 510             def is_file(self, follow_symlinks=True):
 511                 if (self._d_type == DT_UNKNOWN or
 512                         (follow_symlinks and self.is_symlink())):
 513                     try:
 514                         st = self.stat(follow_symlinks=follow_symlinks)
 515                     except OSError as e:
 516                         if e.errno != ENOENT:
 517                             raise
 518                         return False
 519                     return st.st_mode & 0o170000 == S_IFREG
 520                 else:
 521                     return self._d_type == DT_REG
 522 
 523             def is_symlink(self):
 524                 if self._d_type == DT_UNKNOWN:
 525                     try:
 526                         st = self.stat(follow_symlinks=False)
 527                     except OSError as e:
 528                         if e.errno != ENOENT:
 529                             raise
 530                         return False
 531                     return st.st_mode & 0o170000 == S_IFLNK
 532                 else:
 533                     return self._d_type == DT_LNK
 534 
 535             def inode(self):
 536                 return self._inode
 537 
 538             def __str__(self):
 539                 return '<{0}: {1!r}>'.format(self.__class__.__name__, self.name)
 540 
 541             __repr__ = __str__
 542 
 543         def posix_error(filename):
 544             errno = ctypes.get_errno()
 545             exc = OSError(errno, strerror(errno))
 546             exc.filename = filename
 547             return exc
 548 
 549         def scandir_python(path=unicode('.')):
 550             """Like os.listdir(), but yield DirEntry objects instead of returning
 551             a list of names.
 552             """
 553             if isinstance(path, bytes):
 554                 opendir_path = path
 555                 is_bytes = True
 556             else:
 557                 opendir_path = path.encode(file_system_encoding)
 558                 is_bytes = False
 559             dir_p = opendir(opendir_path)
 560             if not dir_p:
 561                 raise posix_error(path)
 562             try:
 563                 result = Dirent_p()
 564                 while True:
 565                     entry = Dirent()
 566                     if readdir_r(dir_p, entry, result):
 567                         raise posix_error(path)
 568                     if not result:
 569                         break
 570                     name = entry.d_name
 571                     if name not in (b'.', b'..'):
 572                         if not is_bytes:
 573                             name = name.decode(file_system_encoding)
 574                         yield PosixDirEntry(path, name, entry.d_type, entry.d_ino)
 575             finally:
 576                 if closedir(dir_p):
 577                     raise posix_error(path)
 578 
 579     if _scandir is not None:
 580         scandir_c = _scandir.scandir
 581         DirEntry_c = _scandir.DirEntry
 582 
 583     if _scandir is not None:
 584         scandir = scandir_c
 585         DirEntry = DirEntry_c
 586     elif ctypes is not None and have_dirent_d_type:
 587         scandir = scandir_python
 588         DirEntry = PosixDirEntry
 589     else:
 590         scandir = scandir_generic
 591         DirEntry = GenericDirEntry
 592 
 593 
 594 # Some other system -- no d_type or stat information
 595 else:
 596     scandir = scandir_generic
 597     DirEntry = GenericDirEntry
 598 
 599 
 600 def _walk(top, topdown=True, onerror=None, followlinks=False):
 601     """Like Python 3.5's implementation of os.walk() -- faster than
 602     the pre-Python 3.5 version as it uses scandir() internally.
 603     """
 604     dirs = []
 605     nondirs = []
 606 
 607     # We may not have read permission for top, in which case we can't
 608     # get a list of the files the directory contains.  os.walk
 609     # always suppressed the exception then, rather than blow up for a
 610     # minor reason when (say) a thousand readable directories are still
 611     # left to visit.  That logic is copied here.
 612     try:
 613         scandir_it = scandir(top)
 614     except OSError as error:
 615         if onerror is not None:
 616             onerror(error)
 617         return
 618 
 619     while True:
 620         try:
 621             try:
 622                 entry = next(scandir_it)
 623             except StopIteration:
 624                 break
 625         except OSError as error:
 626             if onerror is not None:
 627                 onerror(error)
 628             return
 629 
 630         try:
 631             is_dir = entry.is_dir()
 632         except OSError:
 633             # If is_dir() raises an OSError, consider that the entry is not
 634             # a directory, same behaviour than os.path.isdir().
 635             is_dir = False
 636 
 637         if is_dir:
 638             dirs.append(entry.name)
 639         else:
 640             nondirs.append(entry.name)
 641 
 642         if not topdown and is_dir:
 643             # Bottom-up: recurse into sub-directory, but exclude symlinks to
 644             # directories if followlinks is False
 645             if followlinks:
 646                 walk_into = True
 647             else:
 648                 try:
 649                     is_symlink = entry.is_symlink()
 650                 except OSError:
 651                     # If is_symlink() raises an OSError, consider that the
 652                     # entry is not a symbolic link, same behaviour than
 653                     # os.path.islink().
 654                     is_symlink = False
 655                 walk_into = not is_symlink
 656 
 657             if walk_into:
 658                 for entry in walk(entry.path, topdown, onerror, followlinks):
 659                     yield entry
 660 
 661     # Yield before recursion if going top down
 662     if topdown:
 663         yield top, dirs, nondirs
 664 
 665         # Recurse into sub-directories
 666         for name in dirs:
 667             new_path = join(top, name)
 668             # Issue #23605: os.path.islink() is used instead of caching
 669             # entry.is_symlink() result during the loop on os.scandir() because
 670             # the caller can replace the directory entry during the "yield"
 671             # above.
 672             if followlinks or not islink(new_path):
 673                 for entry in walk(new_path, topdown, onerror, followlinks):
 674                     yield entry
 675     else:
 676         # Yield after recursion if going bottom up
 677         yield top, dirs, nondirs
 678 
 679 
 680 if IS_PY3 or sys.platform != 'win32':
 681     walk = _walk
 682 else:
 683     # Fix for broken unicode handling on Windows on Python 2.x, see:
 684     # https://github.com/benhoyt/scandir/issues/54
 685     file_system_encoding = sys.getfilesystemencoding()
 686 
 687     def walk(top, topdown=True, onerror=None, followlinks=False):
 688         if isinstance(top, bytes):
 689             top = top.decode(file_system_encoding)
 690         return _walk(top, topdown, onerror, followlinks)
